@muskangarg21 : the input we deal with is far from perfect. We have ingredients lists in French that use , or . as the decimal sign, and same for other languages. (it can be from the package itself, or from what users enter).
So we try to be very liberal in what we accept, and to do what seems to be the right thing for each different case.
e.g. if we have 2,343 as input for English, we will convert it to 2343. But if we have 2,50 in English, it is probably 2.50, and there is very little chance that it is 250.

